The following report is an exploratory analysis of interest rates on housing and mortgage-related loans in Kaggles (Kaggle.com) Lending Club dataset. After initial data preparation and feature engineering, I employ three machine learning models, a conditional inference forest (cforest) and soft-margin support-vector machine (SVM) for predicting loan grade classifications, and a LASSO regression to predict interest rates on these housing-related loans.

The below plot highlights the distribution of loan amounts in the Lending Club Dataset. It also displays the liklihood that a random withdrawer is in trouble of defaulting. Roughly 2.5% of the persons recorded in the dataset have loan statuses indicative of a potential default.

The below code involves feature engineering in which I attempt to reduce the dimension of my feature vectors into a more maneagable length of 10 predictors. For instance, I create a variable circulated that combines the insights generated by a persons revolving balance along all current credit lines and their total number of open credit accounts to generate a proxy statistic for the extent to which ones credit is distributed across different accounts. I also modify the existing loan_status field of the LendingClub dataset to group together all potential default-prone statuses into a binary fail (0) marker. This choice will reduce the number of levels of this factor in turn reducing the variance of the models I test on during subsequent trials. I finally created a loan/mth field that combines the total loan amount and its term length into one variable, once again reducing the dimensionality of my predictor space.

sub <- loans[,c("id","loan_amnt","funded_amnt","term","int_rate","grade","emp_title","home_ownership",
                "annual_inc","loan_status","pymnt_plan","purpose","annual_inc_joint","open_il_12m","max_bal_bc",
                "total_acc","revol_bal","mths_since_last_delinq")]
sub$default <- loans$potentialDefault
sub <- within(sub,rm("max_bal_bc","open_il_12m","annual_inc_joint","pymnt_plan"))
house <- sub[which(sub$purpose == "house"),]
house <- within(house,rm("purpose","emp_title"))
house$revol_util <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"revol_util"]
house$zip <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"zip_code"]
house$state <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"addr_state"]
house$dti <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"dti"]
house$loc <- gsub(" ","",paste(house$state,house$zip),fixed=T)
house <- within(house,rm("zip","state","funded_amnt"))
house[which(is.na(house$revol_util)),"revol_util"] <- median(house[which(!is.na(house$revol_util)),"revol_util"])
house[which(is.na(house$mths_since_last_delinq)),"mths_since_last_delinq"] <- median(house[which(!is.na(house$mths_since_last_delinq)),"mths_since_last_delinq"])
house$open_acc <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"open_acc"]
house$sub_grade <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"sub_grade"]
house$circulated <- round(house$revol_bal/(house$open_acc * 1.0),2)
house <- within(house,rm("revol_bal","open_acc"))
house$default <- loans[which(loans$purpose == "house"),"loan_status"]
house$term <- as.factor(house$term)
house$grade <- as.factor(house$grade)
house$loan_status <- as.factor(house$loan_status)
house$loc <- as.factor(house$loc)
house$sub_grade <- as.factor(house$sub_grade)
house$home_ownership <- as.factor(house$home_ownership)
house <- within(house,rm("sub_grade"))
house$termLength <- sub(' ','',sapply(as.character(house$term),FUN=function(x){as.integer(strsplit(x," ")[[1]][[2]])}))
house$termLength <- as.integer(house$termLength)
house$loan_mth <- round(house$loan_amnt/(house$termLength * 1.0),2)
housePred <- within(house,rm("loan_amnt","termLength","term"))
housePred$default <- as.factor(housePred$default)
nearZeroVar(housePred,saveMetrics = T)

The below code represents a soft-margin support-vector machine approach (SVM) to classify a persons potential loan into one of the 7 loan grades (A-G) assigned by the Lending Club. The SVM uses a radial kernel, as typically used, and iterates over 100 potential cost penalties to optimize the success rate of the SVMs classification. The final success rate is aproximately 71%, significantly greater than the null rate of roughly 14%-25% by either guessing randomly among the 7 potential loan grades or choosing the most likely grade (C) among all persons represented in the dataset.

SVM Accuracy Rate: 0.71 (when validated on sample of test data)

# predict grade by classification using support-vector machines (SVM) (2)
acc <- array(dim=500)
names(houseTrain)
##  [1] "grade"          "home_ownership" "annual_inc"     "total_acc"     
##  [5] "default"        "revol_util"     "dti"            "loc"           
##  [9] "circulated"     "loan_mth"
for(i in 1:500) {
  svm.loans <- svm(grade~.-annual_inc-total_acc-circulated,data=houseTrain,kernel="radial",scale=T,cost=i)
  svm.predict <- predict(svm.loans,newdata=houseTest,decision.values=T)
  acc[i] = round(mean(svm.predict == houseTest$grade),5)
}
cost <- which(acc == max(acc))[[1]]
svm.loans <- svm(grade~.-annual_inc-total_acc-circulated,data=houseTrain,kernel="radial",scale=T,cost=cost)
svm.predict <- predict(svm.loans,newdata=houseTest,decision.values=T)

The below code implements a LASSO regression analysis to predict the interest_rates on housing and mortgage-related loans. The choice to implement a LASSO regression was one of both convenience and practicality. With as many variables as were present in the original dataset, the LASSOs ability to force both the shrinkage and effective elimination of less significant predictors on the target was attractive. Additionally, a well-trained LASSO is a more robust statistical tool (because of its shrinkage penalties) than ordinary Least-Squares and so I felt it would be a more apt regression tool to use to approximate the interest rates of value in my analysis.

RMSE/Range = ~6.30%

# predict interest rate using LASSO (1)
houseTrain$int_rate <- housePred[inTrain[1:1500],"int_rate"]
houseTest <- (within(housePred,rm("id"))[-inTrain,])[1:500,]
lasso.bind <- rbind(houseTrain,houseTest)
lasso_matrix <- model.matrix(int_rate~.-loc-total_acc,data=lasso.bind)
house.lasso <- glmnet(lasso_matrix[1:1500,],lasso.bind[1:1500,"int_rate"])

lasso.predDF <- model.matrix(int_rate~.-loc-total_acc,data=lasso.bind[1501:2000,])
lasso.pred <- predict(house.lasso,lasso.predDF)
y <- lasso.bind[1501:2000,"int_rate"]
rmse.lasso <- sqrt(apply((y-lasso.pred)^2,2,mean))
lam.best <- house.lasso$lambda[order(rmse.lasso)[1]]
index <- which(house.lasso$lambda == lam.best)
lasso.coef <- coef(house.lasso,s=lam.best) # extract coefficients

best_pred <- lasso.pred[,index] # best predictions
range <- range(y)[[2]]-range(y)[[1]]
